_text":"Sherman Pierpont","notes":"Both Hooker descendants drowned in lakes — Sherman Pierpont in Lake Erie at Sandusky Ohio on May 7, 1836, his body washed ashore three weeks later. Albert Norton Butler in Lake Garfield at Monterey Massachusetts on September 28, 1915, when his rowboat capsized. Seventy-nine years and two generations apart, both Connecticut-origin Hooker descendants ended their lives in lake waters away from their home parishes."}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"education","header":"Yale 1900, then coal and lumber business","body":"He graduated from Yale College in the Class of 1900 — twenty-eight years after his uncle Dr. Henry Cyprian Hart had taken Yale's M.D. degree at the same age. He entered the coal and lumber business and rose to the presidency of Butler & Klein Lumber Company."},{"number":2,"category":"death","header":"Drowned at thirty-eight when his rowboat capsized","body":"On September 28, 1915 at Monterey, Massachusetts, his rowboat capsized on Lake Garfield and he drowned. He was thirty-eight, married, with no surviving children. He was buried at Walnut Grove Cemetery in Meriden — the same yard as his parents."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"albert-butler-1877"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}